  <div class="poem">
    <h3 style="margin-top:0; font-size:1.1rem;">A Slightly Cheeky Poem on the Subject</h3>
    <p>In the glass we meet the ancient score —<br>
    jaw, skin, hair, the tilt of eye and more.<br>
    Not vanity's lone altar, though it plays the part,<br>
    but the quiet ledger where the world takes its start.<br><br>

    The man who sharpens what the years have blurred<br>
    buys himself a margin, a second look, a word<br>
    that lands softer, a door that opens wider,<br>
    a room that rearranges when he walks inside her<br>
    line of sight. And yet the joke is old and true:<br>
    the face you polish still belongs to you.<br><br>

    So train the neck, the sleep, the steady plate,<br>
    the cream at night, the cut that flatters fate.<br>
    But keep the ledger honest, cheek to cheek —<br>
    the best maxxing ends when the mirror looks back and you like what you see, not what the numbers say you ought to be.
    </p>
